dixeram for dixi. Cf. v. 17. iuero for ibo. The use of the fut. pf. for the fut. is a feature of colloquial Latin. Cf. Mil. 3. 2. 50 reuenero ; Trin. 3. 1. 24 abscessero, etc.

Aer II. SCENE Ι.

The captives, being left with the overseers on the stage, get permission to have a private talk. They discuss their plot to personate each other, so that Philocrates may get his liberty and Tyndarus be left as a hostage. This scene is a canticum, i.e. a song, or musical recitative, as opposed to a diverbium, i. e. a dialogue unaccompanied by music. (See Intro- duction, p. 21.)
